s of W.-M. Stock and L. Bergemann; theories of beauty are at the centre of interest of the papers by S. Mariev and M. Marchetto. A. Pizzone approaches Byzantine aesthetics by looking for aesthetic experience in the literary texts, while the remaining contributions explore issues related to the iconoclast controversy: An important moment in the development of Byzantine philosophy on the eve of iconoclasm is the primary interest of A. del Campo Echevarría, who looks at the question of universals in John of Damaskos. The relationship between image and text in Byzantine illustrated manuscripts occupies the attention of B. Crostini. D. Afinogenov explores from a philological perspective the fate of important iconophile terminology in Old Bulgarian, while L. Lukhovitskij reconstructs from historical and philological perspectives the historical memory of the iconoclast controversy during the Late Byzantine Period.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChristianityvByzantine Empire. 0aChristianityzByzantine Empire. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aTheurgyvByzantine Empire. 0aTheurgyzByzantine Empire. 4aByzanz. 4aÄsthetik. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aByzantine Studies.  aTheurgy.1 aAfinogenov, Dmitry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergemann, Lutz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrostini, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchevarría, Alberto del Campo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLukhovitskij, Lev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchetto, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMariev, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul